Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation and confirm:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (hardware/gesture back) and hook into Shell's `Navigating` event for the shell back button:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override void OnAppearing()
    {
        base.OnAppearing();
        Shell.Current.Navigating += OnShellNavigating;
    }

    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();
        Shell.Current.Navigating -= OnShellNavigating;
    }

    // Handles Shell back button / URI navigation
    private async void OnShellNavigating(object sender, ShellNavigatingEventArgs e)
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges || e.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Push)
            return;

        var deferral = e.GetDeferral();

        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave)
            e.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }

    // Handles Android/hardware back button
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        });

        return true; // true = cancel default back behavior
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button:**

Replace Shell's default back arrow via `Shell.BackButtonBehavior`:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior Command="{Binding CancelCommand}"
                           TextOverride="Cancel" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
// The custom button bypasses OnShellNavigating, so handle it explicitly:
public ICommand CancelCommand => new Command(async () =>
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave) return;
    }

    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
});
```

**Key points:**

- **`e.GetDeferral()`** lets you `await` the dialog before deciding to cancel — without it the navigation completes immediately.
- **`OnBackButtonPressed`** only fires for the Android/device back button; `Shell.Navigating` covers the shell chrome back button.
- **`BackButtonBehavior`** with a `Command` replaces the default back arrow entirely, so your command owns the navigation logic.
